    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre connection between two or more quantum particles, where their fates become intertwined no matter the distance separating them. Measuring a property of one entangled particle instantly influences the corresponding property of the other. Unlike classical correlation, like knowing two socks are a pair, entanglement means the properties don't have definite values until one is actually measured. This \"spooky action at a distance\" is what makes it fundamentally quantum.",
      "source": "target",
